 59 var zip_MASK_BITS = new Array(

 61     0x0001, 0x0003, 0x0007, 0x000f, 0x001f, 0x003f, 0x007f, 0x00ff,

 83 var zip_HuftList = function() {
 84     this.next = null;
 85     this.list = null;

 88 var zip_HuftNode = function() {
 89     this.e = 0; // number of extra bits or operation
 90     this.b = 0; // number of bits in this code or subcode
 91 
 92     // union
 93     this.n = 0; // literal, length base, or distance base
 94     this.t = null; // (zip_HuftNode) pointer to next level of table
 95 }

 97 var zip_HuftBuild = function(b,	// code lengths in bits (all assumed <= BMAX)
 98 		       n,	// number of codes (assumed <= N_MAX)
 99 		       s,	// number of simple-valued codes (0..s-1)
100 		       d,	// list of base values for non-simple codes
101 		       e,	// list of extra bits for non-simple codes
102 		       mm	// maximum lookup bits
103 		   ) {
104     this.BMAX = 16;   // maximum bit length of any code
105     this.N_MAX = 288; // maximum number of codes in any set
106     this.status = 0;	// 0: success, 1: incomplete table, 2: bad input
107     this.root = null;	// (zip_HuftList) starting table
108     this.m = 0;		// maximum lookup bits, returns actual
109 
110 /* Given a list of code lengths and a maximum table size, make a set of
111    tables to decode that set of codes.	Return zero on success, one if
112    the given code set is incomplete (the tables are still built in this
113    case), two if the input is invalid (all zero length codes or an
114    oversubscribed set of lengths), and three if not enough memory.
115    The code with value 256 is special, and the tables are constructed
116    so that no bits beyond that code are fetched when that code is
117    decoded. */
118     {
119 	var a;			// counter for codes of length k
120 	var c = new Array(this.BMAX+1);	// bit length count table
121 	var el;			// length of EOB code (value 256)
122 	var f;			// i repeats in table every f entries
123 	var g;			// maximum code length
124 	var h;			// table level
125 	var i;			// counter, current code
126 	var j;			// counter
127 	var k;			// number of bits in current code
128 	var lx = new Array(this.BMAX+1);	// stack of bits per table
129 	var p;			// pointer into c[], b[], or v[]
130 	var pidx;		// index of p
131 	var q;			// (zip_HuftNode) points to current table
132 	var r = new zip_HuftNode(); // table entry for structure assignment
133 	var u = new Array(this.BMAX); // zip_HuftNode[BMAX][]  table stack
134 	var v = new Array(this.N_MAX); // values in order of bit length
135 	var w;
136 	var x = new Array(this.BMAX+1);// bit offsets, then code stack
137 	var xp;			// pointer into x or c
138 	var y;			// number of dummy codes added
139 	var z;			// number of entries in current table
140 	var o;
141 	var tail;		// (zip_HuftList)
142 
143 	tail = this.root = null;
144 	for(i = 0; i < c.length; i++)
145 	    c[i] = 0;
146 	for(i = 0; i < lx.length; i++)
147 	    lx[i] = 0;
148 	for(i = 0; i < u.length; i++)
149 	    u[i] = null;
150 	for(i = 0; i < v.length; i++)
151 	    v[i] = 0;
152 	for(i = 0; i < x.length; i++)
153 	    x[i] = 0;
154 
155 	// Generate counts for each bit length
156 	el = n > 256 ? b[256] : this.BMAX; // set length of EOB code, if any
157 	p = b; pidx = 0;
158 	i = n;
159 	do {
160 	    c[p[pidx]]++;	// assume all entries <= BMAX
161 	    pidx++;
162 	} while(--i > 0);
163 	if(c[0] == n) {	// null input--all zero length codes
164 	    this.root = null;
165 	    this.m = 0;
166 	    this.status = 0;
167 	    return;
168 	}
169 
170 	// Find minimum and maximum length, bound *m by those
171 	for(j = 1; j <= this.BMAX; j++)
172 	    if(c[j] != 0)
173 		break;
174 	k = j;			// minimum code length
175 	if(mm < j)
176 	    mm = j;
177 	for(i = this.BMAX; i != 0; i--)
178 	    if(c[i] != 0)
179 		break;
180 	g = i;			// maximum code length
181 	if(mm > i)
182 	    mm = i;
183 
184 	// Adjust last length count to fill out codes, if needed
185 	for(y = 1 << j; j < i; j++, y <<= 1)
186 	    if((y -= c[j]) < 0) {
187 		this.status = 2;	// bad input: more codes than bits
188 		this.m = mm;
189 		return;
190 	    }
191 	if((y -= c[i]) < 0) {
192 	    this.status = 2;
193 	    this.m = mm;
194 	    return;
195 	}
196 	c[i] += y;
197 
198 	// Generate starting offsets into the value table for each length
199 	x[1] = j = 0;
200 	p = c;
201 	pidx = 1;
202 	xp = 2;
203 	while(--i > 0)		// note that i == g from above
204 	    x[xp++] = (j += p[pidx++]);
205 
206 	// Make a table of values in order of bit lengths
207 	p = b; pidx = 0;
208 	i = 0;
209 	do {
210 	    if((j = p[pidx++]) != 0)
211 		v[x[j]++] = i;
212 	} while(++i < n);
213 	n = x[g];			// set n to length of v
214 
215 	// Generate the Huffman codes and for each, make the table entries
216 	x[0] = i = 0;		// first Huffman code is zero
217 	p = v; pidx = 0;		// grab values in bit order
218 	h = -1;			// no tables yet--level -1
219 	w = lx[0] = 0;		// no bits decoded yet
220 	q = null;			// ditto
221 	z = 0;			// ditto
222 
223 	// go through the bit lengths (k already is bits in shortest code)
224 	for(; k <= g; k++) {
225 	    a = c[k];
226 	    while(a-- > 0) {
227 		// here i is the Huffman code of length k bits for value p[pidx]
228 		// make tables up to required level
229 		while(k > w + lx[1 + h]) {
230 		    w += lx[1 + h]; // add bits already decoded
231 		    h++;
232 
233 		    // compute minimum size table less than or equal to *m bits
234 		    z = (z = g - w) > mm ? mm : z; // upper limit
235 		    if((f = 1 << (j = k - w)) > a + 1) { // try a k-w bit table
236 			// too few codes for k-w bit table
237 			f -= a + 1;	// deduct codes from patterns left
238 			xp = k;
239 			while(++j < z) { // try smaller tables up to z bits
240 			    if((f <<= 1) <= c[++xp])
241 				break;	// enough codes to use up j bits
242 			    f -= c[xp];	// else deduct codes from patterns
243 			}
244 		    }
245 		    if(w + j > el && w < el)
246 			j = el - w;	// make EOB code end at table
247 		    z = 1 << j;	// table entries for j-bit table
248 		    lx[1 + h] = j; // set table size in stack
249 
250 		    // allocate and link in new table
251 		    q = new Array(z);
252 		    for(o = 0; o < z; o++) {
253 			q[o] = new zip_HuftNode();
254 		    }
255 
256 		    if(tail == null)
257 			tail = this.root = new zip_HuftList();
258 		    else
259 			tail = tail.next = new zip_HuftList();
260 		    tail.next = null;
261 		    tail.list = q;
262 		    u[h] = q;	// table starts after link
263 
264 		    /* connect to last table, if there is one */
265 		    if(h > 0) {
266 			x[h] = i;		// save pattern for backing up
267 			r.b = lx[h];	// bits to dump before this table
268 			r.e = 16 + j;	// bits in this table
269 			r.t = q;		// pointer to this table
270 			j = (i & ((1 << w) - 1)) >> (w - lx[h]);
271 			u[h-1][j].e = r.e;
272 			u[h-1][j].b = r.b;
273 			u[h-1][j].n = r.n;
274 			u[h-1][j].t = r.t;
275 		    }
276 		}
277 
278 		// set up table entry in r
279 		r.b = k - w;
280 		if(pidx >= n)
281 		    r.e = 99;		// out of values--invalid code
282 		else if(p[pidx] < s) {
283 		    r.e = (p[pidx] < 256 ? 16 : 15); // 256 is end-of-block code
284 		    r.n = p[pidx++];	// simple code is just the value
285 		} else {
286 		    r.e = e[p[pidx] - s];	// non-simple--look up in lists
287 		    r.n = d[p[pidx++] - s];
288 		}
289 
290 		// fill code-like entries with r //
291 		f = 1 << (k - w);
292 		for(j = i >> w; j < z; j += f) {
293 		    q[j].e = r.e;
294 		    q[j].b = r.b;
295 		    q[j].n = r.n;
296 		    q[j].t = r.t;
297 		}
298 
299 		// backwards increment the k-bit code i
300 		for(j = 1 << (k - 1); (i & j) != 0; j >>= 1)
301 		    i ^= j;
302 		i ^= j;
303 
304 		// backup over finished tables
305 		while((i & ((1 << w) - 1)) != x[h]) {
306 		    w -= lx[h];		// don't need to update q
307 		    h--;
308 		}
309 	    }
310 	}
311 
312 	/* return actual size of base table */
313 	this.m = lx[1];
314 
315 	/* Return true (1) if we were given an incomplete table */
316 	this.status = ((y != 0 && g != 1) ? 1 : 0);
317     } /* end of constructor */
318 }

323 var zip_GET_BYTE = function() {
324     if(zip_inflate_data.length == zip_inflate_pos)
325 	return -1;
326     return zip_inflate_data.charCodeAt(zip_inflate_pos++) & 0xff;
327 }
328 
329 var zip_NEEDBITS = function(n) {
330     while(zip_bit_len < n) {
331 	zip_bit_buf |= zip_GET_BYTE() << zip_bit_len;
332 	zip_bit_len += 8;
333     }
334 }
335 
336 var zip_GETBITS = function(n) {
337     return zip_bit_buf & zip_MASK_BITS[n];
338 }
339 
340 var zip_DUMPBITS = function(n) {
341     zip_bit_buf >>= n;
342     zip_bit_len -= n;
343 }
344 
345 var zip_inflate_codes = function(buff, off, size) {
346     /* inflate (decompress) the codes in a deflated (compressed) block.
347        Return an error code or zero if it all goes ok. */
348     var e;		// table entry flag/number of extra bits
349     var t;		// (zip_HuftNode) pointer to table entry
350     var n;
351 
352     if(size == 0)
353       return 0;
354 
355     // inflate the coded data
356     n = 0;
357     for(;;) {			// do until end of block
358 	zip_NEEDBITS(zip_bl);
359 	t = zip_tl.list[zip_GETBITS(zip_bl)];
360 	e = t.e;
361 	while(e > 16) {
362 	    if(e == 99)
363 		return -1;
364 	    zip_DUMPBITS(t.b);
365 	    e -= 16;
366 	    zip_NEEDBITS(e);
367 	    t = t.t[zip_GETBITS(e)];
368 	    e = t.e;
369 	}
370 	zip_DUMPBITS(t.b);
371 
372 	if(e == 16) {		// then it's a literal
373 	    zip_wp &= zip_WSIZE - 1;
374 	    buff[off + n++] = zip_slide[zip_wp++] = t.n;
375 	    if(n == size)
376 		return size;
377 	    continue;
378 	}
379 
380 	// exit if end of block
381 	if(e == 15)
382 	    break;
383 
384 	// it's an EOB or a length
385 
386 	// get length of block to copy
387 	zip_NEEDBITS(e);
388 	zip_copy_leng = t.n + zip_GETBITS(e);
389 	zip_DUMPBITS(e);
390 
391 	// decode distance of block to copy
392 	zip_NEEDBITS(zip_bd);
393 	t = zip_td.list[zip_GETBITS(zip_bd)];
394 	e = t.e;
395 
396 	while(e > 16) {
397 	    if(e == 99)
398 		return -1;
399 	    zip_DUMPBITS(t.b);
400 	    e -= 16;
401 	    zip_NEEDBITS(e);
402 	    t = t.t[zip_GETBITS(e)];
403 	    e = t.e;
404 	}
405 	zip_DUMPBITS(t.b);
406 	zip_NEEDBITS(e);
407 	zip_copy_dist = zip_wp - t.n - zip_GETBITS(e);
408 	zip_DUMPBITS(e);
409 
410 	// do the copy
411 	while(zip_copy_leng > 0 && n < size) {
412 	    zip_copy_leng--;
413 	    zip_copy_dist &= zip_WSIZE - 1;
414 	    zip_wp &= zip_WSIZE - 1;
415 	    buff[off + n++] = zip_slide[zip_wp++]
416 		= zip_slide[zip_copy_dist++];
417 	}
418 
419 	if(n == size)
420 	    return size;
421     }
422 
423     zip_method = -1; // done
424     return n;
425 }

427 var zip_inflate_stored = function(buff, off, size) {
428     /* "decompress" an inflated type 0 (stored) block. */
429     var n;
430 
431     // go to byte boundary
432     n = zip_bit_len & 7;
433     zip_DUMPBITS(n);
434 
435     // get the length and its complement
436     zip_NEEDBITS(16);
437     n = zip_GETBITS(16);
438     zip_DUMPBITS(16);
439     zip_NEEDBITS(16);
440     if(n != ((~zip_bit_buf) & 0xffff))
441 	return -1;			// error in compressed data
442     zip_DUMPBITS(16);
443 
444     // read and output the compressed data
445     zip_copy_leng = n;
446 
447     n = 0;
448     while(zip_copy_leng > 0 && n < size) {
449 	zip_copy_leng--;
450 	zip_wp &= zip_WSIZE - 1;
451 	zip_NEEDBITS(8);
452 	buff[off + n++] = zip_slide[zip_wp++] =
453 	    zip_GETBITS(8);
454 	zip_DUMPBITS(8);
455     }
456 
457     if(zip_copy_leng == 0)
458       zip_method = -1; // done
459     return n;
460 }

462 var zip_inflate_fixed = function(buff, off, size) {
463     /* decompress an inflated type 1 (fixed Huffman codes) block.  We should
464        either replace this with a custom decoder, or at least precompute the
465        Huffman tables. */
466 
467     // if first time, set up tables for fixed blocks
468     if(zip_fixed_tl == null) {
469 	var i;			// temporary variable
470 	var l = new Array(288);	// length list for huft_build
471 	var h;	// zip_HuftBuild
472 
473 	// literal table
474 	for(i = 0; i < 144; i++)
475 	    l[i] = 8;
476 	for(; i < 256; i++)
477 	    l[i] = 9;
478 	for(; i < 280; i++)
479 	    l[i] = 7;
480 	for(; i < 288; i++)	// make a complete, but wrong code set
481 	    l[i] = 8;
482 	zip_fixed_bl = 7;
483 
484 	h = new zip_HuftBuild(l, 288, 257, zip_cplens, zip_cplext,
485 			      zip_fixed_bl);
486 	if(h.status != 0) {
487 	    alert("HufBuild error: "+h.status);
488 	    return -1;
489 	}
490 	zip_fixed_tl = h.root;
491 	zip_fixed_bl = h.m;
492 
493 	// distance table
494 	for(i = 0; i < 30; i++)	// make an incomplete code set
495 	    l[i] = 5;
496 	zip_fixed_bd = 5;
497 
498 	h = new zip_HuftBuild(l, 30, 0, zip_cpdist, zip_cpdext, zip_fixed_bd);
499 	if(h.status > 1) {
500 	    zip_fixed_tl = null;
501 	    alert("HufBuild error: "+h.status);
502 	    return -1;
503 	}
504 	zip_fixed_td = h.root;
505 	zip_fixed_bd = h.m;
506     }
507 
508     zip_tl = zip_fixed_tl;
509     zip_td = zip_fixed_td;
510     zip_bl = zip_fixed_bl;
511     zip_bd = zip_fixed_bd;
512     return zip_inflate_codes(buff, off, size);
513 }

515 var zip_inflate_dynamic = function(buff, off, size) {
516     // decompress an inflated type 2 (dynamic Huffman codes) block.
517     var i;		// temporary variables
518     var j;
519     var l;		// last length
520     var n;		// number of lengths to get
521     var t;		// (zip_HuftNode) literal/length code table
522     var nb;		// number of bit length codes
523     var nl;		// number of literal/length codes
524     var nd;		// number of distance codes
525     var ll = new Array(286+30); // literal/length and distance code lengths
526     var h;		// (zip_HuftBuild)
527 
528     for(i = 0; i < ll.length; i++)
529 	ll[i] = 0;
530 
531     // read in table lengths
532     zip_NEEDBITS(5);
533     nl = 257 + zip_GETBITS(5);	// number of literal/length codes
534     zip_DUMPBITS(5);
535     zip_NEEDBITS(5);
536     nd = 1 + zip_GETBITS(5);	// number of distance codes
537     zip_DUMPBITS(5);
538     zip_NEEDBITS(4);
539     nb = 4 + zip_GETBITS(4);	// number of bit length codes
540     zip_DUMPBITS(4);
541     if(nl > 286 || nd > 30)
542       return -1;		// bad lengths
543 
544     // read in bit-length-code lengths
545     for(j = 0; j < nb; j++)
546     {
547 	zip_NEEDBITS(3);
548 	ll[zip_border[j]] = zip_GETBITS(3);
549 	zip_DUMPBITS(3);
550     }
551     for(; j < 19; j++)
552 	ll[zip_border[j]] = 0;
553 
554     // build decoding table for trees--single level, 7 bit lookup
555     zip_bl = 7;
556     h = new zip_HuftBuild(ll, 19, 19, null, null, zip_bl);
557     if(h.status != 0)
558 	return -1;	// incomplete code set
559 
560     zip_tl = h.root;
561     zip_bl = h.m;
562 
563     // read in literal and distance code lengths
564     n = nl + nd;
565     i = l = 0;
566     while(i < n) {
567 	zip_NEEDBITS(zip_bl);
568 	t = zip_tl.list[zip_GETBITS(zip_bl)];
569 	j = t.b;
570 	zip_DUMPBITS(j);
571 	j = t.n;
572 	if(j < 16)		// length of code in bits (0..15)
573 	    ll[i++] = l = j;	// save last length in l
574 	else if(j == 16) {	// repeat last length 3 to 6 times
575 	    zip_NEEDBITS(2);
576 	    j = 3 + zip_GETBITS(2);
577 	    zip_DUMPBITS(2);
578 	    if(i + j > n)
579 		return -1;
580 	    while(j-- > 0)
581 		ll[i++] = l;
582 	} else if(j == 17) {	// 3 to 10 zero length codes
583 	    zip_NEEDBITS(3);
584 	    j = 3 + zip_GETBITS(3);
585 	    zip_DUMPBITS(3);
586 	    if(i + j > n)
587 		return -1;
588 	    while(j-- > 0)
589 		ll[i++] = 0;
590 	    l = 0;
591 	} else {		// j == 18: 11 to 138 zero length codes
592 	    zip_NEEDBITS(7);
593 	    j = 11 + zip_GETBITS(7);
594 	    zip_DUMPBITS(7);
595 	    if(i + j > n)
596 		return -1;
597 	    while(j-- > 0)
598 		ll[i++] = 0;
599 	    l = 0;
600 	}
601     }
602 
603     // build the decoding tables for literal/length and distance codes
604     zip_bl = zip_lbits;
605     h = new zip_HuftBuild(ll, nl, 257, zip_cplens, zip_cplext, zip_bl);
606     if(zip_bl == 0)	// no literals or lengths
607 	h.status = 1;
608     if(h.status != 0) {
609 	if(h.status == 1)
610 	    ;// **incomplete literal tree**
611 	return -1;		// incomplete code set
612     }
613     zip_tl = h.root;
614     zip_bl = h.m;
615 
616     for(i = 0; i < nd; i++)
617 	ll[i] = ll[i + nl];
618     zip_bd = zip_dbits;
619     h = new zip_HuftBuild(ll, nd, 0, zip_cpdist, zip_cpdext, zip_bd);
620     zip_td = h.root;
621     zip_bd = h.m;
622 
623     if(zip_bd == 0 && nl > 257) {   // lengths but no distances
624 	// **incomplete distance tree**
625 	return -1;
626     }
627 
628     if(h.status == 1) {
629 	;// **incomplete distance tree**
630     }
631     if(h.status != 0)
632 	return -1;
633 
634     // decompress until an end-of-block code
635     return zip_inflate_codes(buff, off, size);
636 }
637 
638 var zip_inflate_start = function() {
639     var i;
640 
641     if(zip_slide == null)
642 	zip_slide = new Array(2 * zip_WSIZE);
643     zip_wp = 0;
644     zip_bit_buf = 0;
645     zip_bit_len = 0;
646     zip_method = -1;
647     zip_eof = false;
648     zip_copy_leng = zip_copy_dist = 0;
649     zip_tl = null;
650 }
651 
652 var zip_inflate_internal = function(buff, off, size) {
653     // decompress an inflated entry
654     var n, i;
655 
656     n = 0;
657     while(n < size) {
658 	if(zip_eof && zip_method == -1)
659 	    return n;
660 
661 	if(zip_copy_leng > 0) {
662 	    if(zip_method != zip_STORED_BLOCK) {
663 		// STATIC_TREES or DYN_TREES
664 		while(zip_copy_leng > 0 && n < size) {
665 		    zip_copy_leng--;
666 		    zip_copy_dist &= zip_WSIZE - 1;
667 		    zip_wp &= zip_WSIZE - 1;
668 		    buff[off + n++] = zip_slide[zip_wp++] =
669 			zip_slide[zip_copy_dist++];
670 		}
671 	    } else {
672 		while(zip_copy_leng > 0 && n < size) {
673 		    zip_copy_leng--;
674 		    zip_wp &= zip_WSIZE - 1;
675 		    zip_NEEDBITS(8);
676 		    buff[off + n++] = zip_slide[zip_wp++] = zip_GETBITS(8);
677 		    zip_DUMPBITS(8);
678 		}
679 		if(zip_copy_leng == 0)
680 		    zip_method = -1; // done
681 	    }
682 	    if(n == size)
683 		return n;
684 	}
685 
686 	if(zip_method == -1) {
687 	    if(zip_eof)
688 		break;
689 
690 	    // read in last block bit
691 	    zip_NEEDBITS(1);
692 	    if(zip_GETBITS(1) != 0)
693 		zip_eof = true;
694 	    zip_DUMPBITS(1);
695 
696 	    // read in block type
697 	    zip_NEEDBITS(2);
698 	    zip_method = zip_GETBITS(2);
699 	    zip_DUMPBITS(2);
700 	    zip_tl = null;
701 	    zip_copy_leng = 0;
702 	}
703 
704 	switch(zip_method) {
705 	  case 0: // zip_STORED_BLOCK
706 	    i = zip_inflate_stored(buff, off + n, size - n);
707 	    break;
708 
709 	  case 1: // zip_STATIC_TREES
710 	    if(zip_tl != null)
711 		i = zip_inflate_codes(buff, off + n, size - n);
712 	    else
713 		i = zip_inflate_fixed(buff, off + n, size - n);
714 	    break;
715 
716 	  case 2: // zip_DYN_TREES
717 	    if(zip_tl != null)
718 		i = zip_inflate_codes(buff, off + n, size - n);
719 	    else
720 		i = zip_inflate_dynamic(buff, off + n, size - n);
721 	    break;
722 
723 	  default: // error
724 	    i = -1;
725 	    break;
726 	}
727 
728 	if(i == -1) {
729 	    if(zip_eof)
730 		return 0;
731 	    return -1;
732 	}
733 	n += i;
734     }
735     return n;
736 }
737 
738 var zip_inflate = function(str) {
739     var i, j;
740 
741     zip_inflate_start();
742     zip_inflate_data = str;
743     zip_inflate_pos = 0;
744 
745     var buff = new Array(1024);
746     var aout = [];
747     while((i = zip_inflate_internal(buff, 0, buff.length)) > 0) {
748 	var cbuf = new Array(i);
749 	for(j = 0; j < i; j++){
750 	    cbuf[j] = String.fromCharCode(buff[j]);
751 	}
752 	aout[aout.length] = cbuf.join("");
753     }
754     zip_inflate_data = null; // G.C.
755     return aout.join("");
756 }
757 
758 if (! window.RawDeflate) RawDeflate = {};
759 RawDeflate.inflate = zip_inflate;
760

1059 /* put_byte is used for the compressed output, put_ubyte for the
1060  * uncompressed output. However unlzw() uses window for its
1061  * suffix table instead of its output buffer, so it does not use put_ubyte
1062  * (to be cleaned up).
1063  */
1064 var zip_put_byte = function(c) {
1065     zip_outbuf[zip_outoff + zip_outcnt++] = c;
1066     if(zip_outoff + zip_outcnt == zip_OUTBUFSIZ)
1067 	zip_qoutbuf();
1068 }

1070 /* Output a 16 bit value, lsb first */
1071 var zip_put_short = function(w) {
1072     w &= 0xffff;
1073     if(zip_outoff + zip_outcnt < zip_OUTBUFSIZ - 2) {
1074 	zip_outbuf[zip_outoff + zip_outcnt++] = (w & 0xff);
1075 	zip_outbuf[zip_outoff + zip_outcnt++] = (w >>> 8);
1076     } else {
1077 	zip_put_byte(w & 0xff);
1078 	zip_put_byte(w >>> 8);
1079     }
1080 }

1082 /* ==========================================================================
1083  * Insert string s in the dictionary and set match_head to the previous head
1084  * of the hash chain (the most recent string with same hash key). Return
1085  * the previous length of the hash chain.
1086  * IN  assertion: all calls to to INSERT_STRING are made with consecutive
1087  *    input characters and the first MIN_MATCH bytes of s are valid
1088  *    (except for the last MIN_MATCH-1 bytes of the input file).
1089  */
1090 var zip_INSERT_STRING = function() {
1091     zip_ins_h = ((zip_ins_h << zip_H_SHIFT)
1092 		 ^ (zip_window[zip_strstart + zip_MIN_MATCH - 1] & 0xff))
1093 	& zip_HASH_MASK;
1094     zip_hash_head = zip_head1(zip_ins_h);
1095     zip_prev[zip_strstart & zip_WMASK] = zip_hash_head;
1096     zip_head2(zip_ins_h, zip_strstart);
1097 }

1099 /* Send a code of the given tree. c and tree must not have side effects */
1100 var zip_SEND_CODE = function(c, tree) {
1101     zip_send_bits(tree[c].fc, tree[c].dl);
1102 }

1104 /* Mapping from a distance to a distance code. dist is the distance - 1 and
1105  * must not have side effects. dist_code[256] and dist_code[257] are never
1106  * used.
1107  */
1108 var zip_D_CODE = function(dist) {
1109     return (dist < 256 ? zip_dist_code[dist]
1110 	    : zip_dist_code[256 + (dist>>7)]) & 0xff;
1111 }

1113 /* ==========================================================================
1114  * Compares to subtrees, using the tree depth as tie breaker when
1115  * the subtrees have equal frequency. This minimizes the worst case length.
1116  */
1117 var zip_SMALLER = function(tree, n, m) {
1118     return tree[n].fc < tree[m].fc ||
1119       (tree[n].fc == tree[m].fc && zip_depth[n] <= zip_depth[m]);
1120 }

1123  * read string data
1124  */
1125 var zip_read_buff = function(buff, offset, n) {
1126     var i;
1127     for(i = 0; i < n && zip_deflate_pos < zip_deflate_data.length; i++)
1128 	buff[offset + i] =
1129 	    zip_deflate_data.charCodeAt(zip_deflate_pos++) & 0xff;
1130     return i;
1131 }

1133 /* ==========================================================================
1134  * Initialize the "longest match" routines for a new file
1135  */
1136 var zip_lm_init = function() {
1137     var j;
1138 
1139     /* Initialize the hash table. */
1140     for(j = 0; j < zip_HASH_SIZE; j++)
1141 //	zip_head2(j, zip_NIL);
1142 	zip_prev[zip_WSIZE + j] = 0;
1143     /* prev will be initialized on the fly */
1144 
1145     /* Set the default configuration parameters:
1146      */
1147     zip_max_lazy_match = zip_configuration_table[zip_compr_level].max_lazy;
1148     zip_good_match     = zip_configuration_table[zip_compr_level].good_length;
1149     if(!zip_FULL_SEARCH)
1150 	zip_nice_match = zip_configuration_table[zip_compr_level].nice_length;
1151     zip_max_chain_length = zip_configuration_table[zip_compr_level].max_chain;
1152 
1153     zip_strstart = 0;
1154     zip_block_start = 0;
1155 
1156     zip_lookahead = zip_read_buff(zip_window, 0, 2 * zip_WSIZE);
1157     if(zip_lookahead <= 0) {
1158 	zip_eofile = true;
1159 	zip_lookahead = 0;
1160 	return;
1161     }
1162     zip_eofile = false;
1163     /* Make sure that we always have enough lookahead. This is important
1164      * if input comes from a device such as a tty.
1165      */
1166     while(zip_lookahead < zip_MIN_LOOKAHEAD && !zip_eofile)
1167 	zip_fill_window();
1168 
1169     /* If lookahead < MIN_MATCH, ins_h is garbage, but this is
1170      * not important since only literal bytes will be emitted.
1171      */
1172     zip_ins_h = 0;
1173     for(j = 0; j < zip_MIN_MATCH - 1; j++) {
1174 //      UPDATE_HASH(ins_h, window[j]);
1175 	zip_ins_h = ((zip_ins_h << zip_H_SHIFT) ^ (zip_window[j] & 0xff)) & zip_HASH_MASK;
1176     }
1177 }
1178 
1179 /* ==========================================================================
1180  * Set match_start to the longest match starting at the given string and
1181  * return its length. Matches shorter or equal to prev_length are discarded,
1182  * in which case the result is equal to prev_length and match_start is
1183  * garbage.
1184  * IN assertions: cur_match is the head of the hash chain for the current
1185  *   string (strstart) and its distance is <= MAX_DIST, and prev_length >= 1
1186  */
1187 var zip_longest_match = function(cur_match) {
1188     var chain_length = zip_max_chain_length; // max hash chain length
1189     var scanp = zip_strstart; // current string
1190     var matchp;		// matched string
1191     var len;		// length of current match
1192     var best_len = zip_prev_length;	// best match length so far
1193 
1194     /* Stop when cur_match becomes <= limit. To simplify the code,
1195      * we prevent matches with the string of window index 0.
1196      */
1197     var limit = (zip_strstart > zip_MAX_DIST ? zip_strstart - zip_MAX_DIST : zip_NIL);
1198 
1199     var strendp = zip_strstart + zip_MAX_MATCH;
1200     var scan_end1 = zip_window[scanp + best_len - 1];
1201     var scan_end  = zip_window[scanp + best_len];
1202 
1203     /* Do not waste too much time if we already have a good match: */
1204     if(zip_prev_length >= zip_good_match)
1205 	chain_length >>= 2;
1206 
1207 //  Assert(encoder->strstart <= window_size-MIN_LOOKAHEAD, "insufficient lookahead");
1208 
1209     do {
1210 //    Assert(cur_match < encoder->strstart, "no future");
1211 	matchp = cur_match;
1212 
1213 	/* Skip to next match if the match length cannot increase
1214 	    * or if the match length is less than 2:
1215 	*/
1216 	if(zip_window[matchp + best_len]	!= scan_end  ||
1217 	   zip_window[matchp + best_len - 1]	!= scan_end1 ||
1218 	   zip_window[matchp]			!= zip_window[scanp] ||
1219 	   zip_window[++matchp]			!= zip_window[scanp + 1]) {
1220 	    continue;
1221 	}
1222 
1223 	/* The check at best_len-1 can be removed because it will be made
1224          * again later. (This heuristic is not always a win.)
1225          * It is not necessary to compare scan[2] and match[2] since they
1226          * are always equal when the other bytes match, given that
1227          * the hash keys are equal and that HASH_BITS >= 8.
1228          */
1229 	scanp += 2;
1230 	matchp++;
1231 
1232 	/* We check for insufficient lookahead only every 8th comparison;
1233          * the 256th check will be made at strstart+258.
1234          */
1235 	do {
1236 	} while(zip_window[++scanp] == zip_window[++matchp] &&
1237 		zip_window[++scanp] == zip_window[++matchp] &&
1238 		zip_window[++scanp] == zip_window[++matchp] &&
1239 		zip_window[++scanp] == zip_window[++matchp] &&
1240 		zip_window[++scanp] == zip_window[++matchp] &&
1241 		zip_window[++scanp] == zip_window[++matchp] &&
1242 		zip_window[++scanp] == zip_window[++matchp] &&
1243 		zip_window[++scanp] == zip_window[++matchp] &&
1244 		scanp < strendp);
1245 
1246       len = zip_MAX_MATCH - (strendp - scanp);
1247       scanp = strendp - zip_MAX_MATCH;
1248 
1249       if(len > best_len) {
1250 	  zip_match_start = cur_match;
1251 	  best_len = len;
1252 	  if(zip_FULL_SEARCH) {
1253 	      if(len >= zip_MAX_MATCH) break;
1254 	  } else {
1255 	      if(len >= zip_nice_match) break;
1256 	  }
1257 
1258 	  scan_end1  = zip_window[scanp + best_len-1];
1259 	  scan_end   = zip_window[scanp + best_len];
1260       }
1261     } while((cur_match = zip_prev[cur_match & zip_WMASK]) > limit
1262 	    && --chain_length != 0);
1263 
1264     return best_len;
1265 }
1266 
1267 /* ==========================================================================
1268  * Fill the window when the lookahead becomes insufficient.
1269  * Updates strstart and lookahead, and sets eofile if end of input file.
1270  * IN assertion: lookahead < MIN_LOOKAHEAD && strstart + lookahead > 0
1271  * OUT assertions: at least one byte has been read, or eofile is set;
1272  *    file reads are performed for at least two bytes (required for the
1273  *    translate_eol option).
1274  */
1275 var zip_fill_window = function() {
1276     var n, m;
1277 
1278     // Amount of free space at the end of the window.
1279     var more = zip_window_size - zip_lookahead - zip_strstart;
1280 
1281     /* If the window is almost full and there is insufficient lookahead,
1282      * move the upper half to the lower one to make room in the upper half.
1283      */
1284     if(more == -1) {
1285 	/* Very unlikely, but possible on 16 bit machine if strstart == 0
1286          * and lookahead == 1 (input done one byte at time)
1287          */
1288 	more--;
1289     } else if(zip_strstart >= zip_WSIZE + zip_MAX_DIST) {
1290 	/* By the IN assertion, the window is not empty so we can't confuse
1291          * more == 0 with more == 64K on a 16 bit machine.
1292          */
1293 //	Assert(window_size == (ulg)2*WSIZE, "no sliding with BIG_MEM");
1294 
1295 //	System.arraycopy(window, WSIZE, window, 0, WSIZE);
1296 	for(n = 0; n < zip_WSIZE; n++)
1297 	    zip_window[n] = zip_window[n + zip_WSIZE];
1298       
1299 	zip_match_start -= zip_WSIZE;
1300 	zip_strstart    -= zip_WSIZE; /* we now have strstart >= MAX_DIST: */
1301 	zip_block_start -= zip_WSIZE;
1302 
1303 	for(n = 0; n < zip_HASH_SIZE; n++) {
1304 	    m = zip_head1(n);
1305 	    zip_head2(n, m >= zip_WSIZE ? m - zip_WSIZE : zip_NIL);
1306 	}
1307 	for(n = 0; n < zip_WSIZE; n++) {
1308 	    /* If n is not on any hash chain, prev[n] is garbage but
1309 	     * its value will never be used.
1310 	     */
1311 	    m = zip_prev[n];
1312 	    zip_prev[n] = (m >= zip_WSIZE ? m - zip_WSIZE : zip_NIL);
1313 	}
1314 	more += zip_WSIZE;
1315     }
1316     // At this point, more >= 2
1317     if(!zip_eofile) {
1318 	n = zip_read_buff(zip_window, zip_strstart + zip_lookahead, more);
1319 	if(n <= 0)
1320 	    zip_eofile = true;
1321 	else
1322 	    zip_lookahead += n;
1323     }
1324 }
1325 
1326 /* ==========================================================================
1327  * Processes a new input file and return its compressed length. This
1328  * function does not perform lazy evaluationof matches and inserts
1329  * new strings in the dictionary only for unmatched strings or for short
1330  * matches. It is used only for the fast compression options.
1331  */
1332 var zip_deflate_fast = function() {
1333     while(zip_lookahead != 0 && zip_qhead == null) {
1334 	var flush; // set if current block must be flushed
1335 
1336 	/* Insert the string window[strstart .. strstart+2] in the
1337 	 * dictionary, and set hash_head to the head of the hash chain:
1338 	 */
1339 	zip_INSERT_STRING();
1340 
1341 	/* Find the longest match, discarding those <= prev_length.
1342 	 * At this point we have always match_length < MIN_MATCH
1343 	 */
1344 	if(zip_hash_head != zip_NIL &&
1345 	   zip_strstart - zip_hash_head <= zip_MAX_DIST) {
1346 	    /* To simplify the code, we prevent matches with the string
1347 	     * of window index 0 (in particular we have to avoid a match
1348 	     * of the string with itself at the start of the input file).
1349 	     */
1350 	    zip_match_length = zip_longest_match(zip_hash_head);
1351 	    /* longest_match() sets match_start */
1352 	    if(zip_match_length > zip_lookahead)
1353 		zip_match_length = zip_lookahead;
1354 	}
1355 	if(zip_match_length >= zip_MIN_MATCH) {
1356 //	    check_match(strstart, match_start, match_length);
1357 
1358 	    flush = zip_ct_tally(zip_strstart - zip_match_start,
1359 				 zip_match_length - zip_MIN_MATCH);
1360 	    zip_lookahead -= zip_match_length;
1361 
1362 	    /* Insert new strings in the hash table only if the match length
1363 	     * is not too large. This saves time but degrades compression.
1364 	     */
1365 	    if(zip_match_length <= zip_max_lazy_match) {
1366 		zip_match_length--; // string at strstart already in hash table
1367 		do {
1368 		    zip_strstart++;
1369 		    zip_INSERT_STRING();
1370 		    /* strstart never exceeds WSIZE-MAX_MATCH, so there are
1371 		     * always MIN_MATCH bytes ahead. If lookahead < MIN_MATCH
1372 		     * these bytes are garbage, but it does not matter since
1373 		     * the next lookahead bytes will be emitted as literals.
1374 		     */
1375 		} while(--zip_match_length != 0);
1376 		zip_strstart++;
1377 	    } else {
1378 		zip_strstart += zip_match_length;
1379 		zip_match_length = 0;
1380 		zip_ins_h = zip_window[zip_strstart] & 0xff;
1381 //		UPDATE_HASH(ins_h, window[strstart + 1]);
1382 		zip_ins_h = ((zip_ins_h<<zip_H_SHIFT) ^ (zip_window[zip_strstart + 1] & 0xff)) & zip_HASH_MASK;
1383 
1384 //#if MIN_MATCH != 3
1385 //		Call UPDATE_HASH() MIN_MATCH-3 more times
1386 //#endif
1387 
1388 	    }
1389 	} else {
1390 	    /* No match, output a literal byte */
1391 	    flush = zip_ct_tally(0, zip_window[zip_strstart] & 0xff);
1392 	    zip_lookahead--;
1393 	    zip_strstart++;
1394 	}
1395 	if(flush) {
1396 	    zip_flush_block(0);
1397 	    zip_block_start = zip_strstart;
1398 	}
1399 
1400 	/* Make sure that we always have enough lookahead, except
1401 	 * at the end of the input file. We need MAX_MATCH bytes
1402 	 * for the next match, plus MIN_MATCH bytes to insert the
1403 	 * string following the next match.
1404 	 */
1405 	while(zip_lookahead < zip_MIN_LOOKAHEAD && !zip_eofile)
1406 	    zip_fill_window();
1407     }
1408 }
1409 
1410 var zip_deflate_better = function() {
1411     /* Process the input block. */
1412     while(zip_lookahead != 0 && zip_qhead == null) {
1413 	/* Insert the string window[strstart .. strstart+2] in the
1414 	 * dictionary, and set hash_head to the head of the hash chain:
1415 	 */
1416 	zip_INSERT_STRING();
1417 
1418 	/* Find the longest match, discarding those <= prev_length.
1419 	 */
1420 	zip_prev_length = zip_match_length;
1421 	zip_prev_match = zip_match_start;
1422 	zip_match_length = zip_MIN_MATCH - 1;
1423 
1424 	if(zip_hash_head != zip_NIL &&
1425 	   zip_prev_length < zip_max_lazy_match &&
1426 	   zip_strstart - zip_hash_head <= zip_MAX_DIST) {
1427 	    /* To simplify the code, we prevent matches with the string
1428 	     * of window index 0 (in particular we have to avoid a match
1429 	     * of the string with itself at the start of the input file).
1430 	     */
1431 	    zip_match_length = zip_longest_match(zip_hash_head);
1432 	    /* longest_match() sets match_start */
1433 	    if(zip_match_length > zip_lookahead)
1434 		zip_match_length = zip_lookahead;
1435 
1436 	    /* Ignore a length 3 match if it is too distant: */
1437 	    if(zip_match_length == zip_MIN_MATCH &&
1438 	       zip_strstart - zip_match_start > zip_TOO_FAR) {
1439 		/* If prev_match is also MIN_MATCH, match_start is garbage
1440 		 * but we will ignore the current match anyway.
1441 		 */
1442 		zip_match_length--;
1443 	    }
1444 	}
1445 	/* If there was a match at the previous step and the current
1446 	 * match is not better, output the previous match:
1447 	 */
1448 	if(zip_prev_length >= zip_MIN_MATCH &&
1449 	   zip_match_length <= zip_prev_length) {
1450 	    var flush; // set if current block must be flushed
1451 
1452 //	    check_match(strstart - 1, prev_match, prev_length);
1453 	    flush = zip_ct_tally(zip_strstart - 1 - zip_prev_match,
1454 				 zip_prev_length - zip_MIN_MATCH);
1455 
1456 	    /* Insert in hash table all strings up to the end of the match.
1457 	     * strstart-1 and strstart are already inserted.
1458 	     */
1459 	    zip_lookahead -= zip_prev_length - 1;
1460 	    zip_prev_length -= 2;
1461 	    do {
1462 		zip_strstart++;
1463 		zip_INSERT_STRING();
1464 		/* strstart never exceeds WSIZE-MAX_MATCH, so there are
1465 		 * always MIN_MATCH bytes ahead. If lookahead < MIN_MATCH
1466 		 * these bytes are garbage, but it does not matter since the
1467 		 * next lookahead bytes will always be emitted as literals.
1468 		 */
1469 	    } while(--zip_prev_length != 0);
1470 	    zip_match_available = 0;
1471 	    zip_match_length = zip_MIN_MATCH - 1;
1472 	    zip_strstart++;
1473 	    if(flush) {
1474 		zip_flush_block(0);
1475 		zip_block_start = zip_strstart;
1476 	    }
1477 	} else if(zip_match_available != 0) {
1478 	    /* If there was no match at the previous position, output a
1479 	     * single literal. If there was a match but the current match
1480 	     * is longer, truncate the previous match to a single literal.
1481 	     */
1482 	    if(zip_ct_tally(0, zip_window[zip_strstart - 1] & 0xff)) {
1483 		zip_flush_block(0);
1484 		zip_block_start = zip_strstart;
1485 	    }
1486 	    zip_strstart++;
1487 	    zip_lookahead--;
1488 	} else {
1489 	    /* There is no previous match to compare with, wait for
1490 	     * the next step to decide.
1491 	     */
1492 	    zip_match_available = 1;
1493 	    zip_strstart++;
1494 	    zip_lookahead--;
1495 	}
1496 
1497 	/* Make sure that we always have enough lookahead, except
1498 	 * at the end of the input file. We need MAX_MATCH bytes
1499 	 * for the next match, plus MIN_MATCH bytes to insert the
1500 	 * string following the next match.
1501 	 */
1502 	while(zip_lookahead < zip_MIN_LOOKAHEAD && !zip_eofile)
1503 	    zip_fill_window();
1504     }
1505 }

1507 var zip_init_deflate = function() {
1508     if(zip_eofile)
1509 	return;
1510     zip_bi_buf = 0;
1511     zip_bi_valid = 0;
1512     zip_ct_init();
1513     zip_lm_init();
1514 
1515     zip_qhead = null;
1516     zip_outcnt = 0;
1517     zip_outoff = 0;
1518 
1519     if(zip_compr_level <= 3)
1520     {
1521 	zip_prev_length = zip_MIN_MATCH - 1;
1522 	zip_match_length = 0;
1523     }
1524     else
1525     {
1526 	zip_match_length = zip_MIN_MATCH - 1;
1527 	zip_match_available = 0;
1528     }
1529 
1530     zip_complete = false;
1531 }
1532 
1533 /* ==========================================================================
1534  * Same as above, but achieves better compression. We use a lazy
1535  * evaluation for matches: a match is finally adopted only if there is
1536  * no better match at the next window position.
1537  */
1538 var zip_deflate_internal = function(buff, off, buff_size) {
1539     var n;
1540 
1541     if(!zip_initflag)
1542     {
1543 	zip_init_deflate();
1544 	zip_initflag = true;
1545 	if(zip_lookahead == 0) { // empty
1546 	    zip_complete = true;
1547 	    return 0;
1548 	}
1549     }
1550 
1551     if((n = zip_qcopy(buff, off, buff_size)) == buff_size)
1552 	return buff_size;
1553 
1554     if(zip_complete)
1555 	return n;
1556 
1557     if(zip_compr_level <= 3) // optimized for speed
1558 	zip_deflate_fast();
1559     else
1560 	zip_deflate_better();
1561     if(zip_lookahead == 0) {
1562 	if(zip_match_available != 0)
1563 	    zip_ct_tally(0, zip_window[zip_strstart - 1] & 0xff);
1564 	zip_flush_block(1);
1565 	zip_complete = true;
1566     }
1567     return n + zip_qcopy(buff, n + off, buff_size - n);
1568 }
1569 
1570 var zip_qcopy = function(buff, off, buff_size) {
1571     var n, i, j;
1572 
1573     n = 0;
1574     while(zip_qhead != null && n < buff_size)
1575     {
1576 	i = buff_size - n;
1577 	if(i > zip_qhead.len)
1578 	    i = zip_qhead.len;
1579 //      System.arraycopy(qhead.ptr, qhead.off, buff, off + n, i);
1580 	for(j = 0; j < i; j++)
1581 	    buff[off + n + j] = zip_qhead.ptr[zip_qhead.off + j];
1582 	
1583 	zip_qhead.off += i;
1584 	zip_qhead.len -= i;
1585 	n += i;
1586 	if(zip_qhead.len == 0) {
1587 	    var p;
1588 	    p = zip_qhead;
1589 	    zip_qhead = zip_qhead.next;
1590 	    zip_reuse_queue(p);
1591 	}
1592     }
1593 
1594     if(n == buff_size)
1595 	return n;
1596 
1597     if(zip_outoff < zip_outcnt) {
1598 	i = buff_size - n;
1599 	if(i > zip_outcnt - zip_outoff)
1600 	    i = zip_outcnt - zip_outoff;
1601 	// System.arraycopy(outbuf, outoff, buff, off + n, i);
1602 	for(j = 0; j < i; j++)
1603 	    buff[off + n + j] = zip_outbuf[zip_outoff + j];
1604 	zip_outoff += i;
1605 	n += i;
1606 	if(zip_outcnt == zip_outoff)
1607 	    zip_outcnt = zip_outoff = 0;
1608     }
1609     return n;
1610 }

1612 /* ==========================================================================
1613  * Allocate the match buffer, initialize the various tables and save the
1614  * location of the internal file attribute (ascii/binary) and method
1615  * (DEFLATE/STORE).
1616  */
1617 var zip_ct_init = function() {
1618     var n;	// iterates over tree elements
1619     var bits;	// bit counter
1620     var length;	// length value
1621     var code;	// code value
1622     var dist;	// distance index
1623 
1624     if(zip_static_dtree[0].dl != 0) return; // ct_init already called
1625 
1626     zip_l_desc.dyn_tree		= zip_dyn_ltree;
1627     zip_l_desc.static_tree	= zip_static_ltree;
1628     zip_l_desc.extra_bits	= zip_extra_lbits;
1629     zip_l_desc.extra_base	= zip_LITERALS + 1;
1630     zip_l_desc.elems		= zip_L_CODES;
1631     zip_l_desc.max_length	= zip_MAX_BITS;
1632     zip_l_desc.max_code		= 0;
1633 
1634     zip_d_desc.dyn_tree		= zip_dyn_dtree;
1635     zip_d_desc.static_tree	= zip_static_dtree;
1636     zip_d_desc.extra_bits	= zip_extra_dbits;
1637     zip_d_desc.extra_base	= 0;
1638     zip_d_desc.elems		= zip_D_CODES;
1639     zip_d_desc.max_length	= zip_MAX_BITS;
1640     zip_d_desc.max_code		= 0;
1641 
1642     zip_bl_desc.dyn_tree	= zip_bl_tree;
1643     zip_bl_desc.static_tree	= null;
1644     zip_bl_desc.extra_bits	= zip_extra_blbits;
1645     zip_bl_desc.extra_base	= 0;
1646     zip_bl_desc.elems		= zip_BL_CODES;
1647     zip_bl_desc.max_length	= zip_MAX_BL_BITS;
1648     zip_bl_desc.max_code	= 0;
1649 
1650     // Initialize the mapping length (0..255) -> length code (0..28)
1651     length = 0;
1652     for(code = 0; code < zip_LENGTH_CODES-1; code++) {
1653 	zip_base_length[code] = length;
1654 	for(n = 0; n < (1<<zip_extra_lbits[code]); n++)
1655 	    zip_length_code[length++] = code;
1656     }
1657     // Assert (length == 256, "ct_init: length != 256");
1658 
1659     /* Note that the length 255 (match length 258) can be represented
1660      * in two different ways: code 284 + 5 bits or code 285, so we
1661      * overwrite length_code[255] to use the best encoding:
1662      */
1663     zip_length_code[length-1] = code;
1664 
1665     /* Initialize the mapping dist (0..32K) -> dist code (0..29) */
1666     dist = 0;
1667     for(code = 0 ; code < 16; code++) {
1668 	zip_base_dist[code] = dist;
1669 	for(n = 0; n < (1<<zip_extra_dbits[code]); n++) {
1670 	    zip_dist_code[dist++] = code;
1671 	}
1672     }
1673     // Assert (dist == 256, "ct_init: dist != 256");
1674     dist >>= 7; // from now on, all distances are divided by 128
1675     for( ; code < zip_D_CODES; code++) {
1676 	zip_base_dist[code] = dist << 7;
1677 	for(n = 0; n < (1<<(zip_extra_dbits[code]-7)); n++)
1678 	    zip_dist_code[256 + dist++] = code;
1679     }
1680     // Assert (dist == 256, "ct_init: 256+dist != 512");
1681 
1682     // Construct the codes of the static literal tree
1683     for(bits = 0; bits <= zip_MAX_BITS; bits++)
1684 	zip_bl_count[bits] = 0;
1685     n = 0;
1686     while(n <= 143) { zip_static_ltree[n++].dl = 8; zip_bl_count[8]++; }
1687     while(n <= 255) { zip_static_ltree[n++].dl = 9; zip_bl_count[9]++; }
1688     while(n <= 279) { zip_static_ltree[n++].dl = 7; zip_bl_count[7]++; }
1689     while(n <= 287) { zip_static_ltree[n++].dl = 8; zip_bl_count[8]++; }
1690     /* Codes 286 and 287 do not exist, but we must include them in the
1691      * tree construction to get a canonical Huffman tree (longest code
1692      * all ones)
1693      */
1694     zip_gen_codes(zip_static_ltree, zip_L_CODES + 1);
1695 
1696     /* The static distance tree is trivial: */
1697     for(n = 0; n < zip_D_CODES; n++) {
1698 	zip_static_dtree[n].dl = 5;
1699 	zip_static_dtree[n].fc = zip_bi_reverse(n, 5);
1700     }
1701 
1702     // Initialize the first block of the first file:
1703     zip_init_block();
1704 }

1706 /* ==========================================================================
1707  * Initialize a new block.
1708  */
1709 var zip_init_block = function() {
1710     var n; // iterates over tree elements
1711 
1712     // Initialize the trees.
1713     for(n = 0; n < zip_L_CODES;  n++) zip_dyn_ltree[n].fc = 0;
1714     for(n = 0; n < zip_D_CODES;  n++) zip_dyn_dtree[n].fc = 0;
1715     for(n = 0; n < zip_BL_CODES; n++) zip_bl_tree[n].fc = 0;
1716 
1717     zip_dyn_ltree[zip_END_BLOCK].fc = 1;
1718     zip_opt_len = zip_static_len = 0;
1719     zip_last_lit = zip_last_dist = zip_last_flags = 0;
1720     zip_flags = 0;
1721     zip_flag_bit = 1;
1722 }
1723 
1724 /* ==========================================================================
1725  * Restore the heap property by moving down the tree starting at node k,
1726  * exchanging a node with the smallest of its two sons if necessary, stopping
1727  * when the heap property is re-established (each father smaller than its
1728  * two sons).
1729  */
1730 var zip_pqdownheap = function(
1731     tree,	// the tree to restore
1732     k) {	// node to move down
1733     var v = zip_heap[k];
1734     var j = k << 1;	// left son of k
1735 
1736     while(j <= zip_heap_len) {
1737 	// Set j to the smallest of the two sons:
1738 	if(j < zip_heap_len &&
1739 	   zip_SMALLER(tree, zip_heap[j + 1], zip_heap[j]))
1740 	    j++;
1741 
1742 	// Exit if v is smaller than both sons
1743 	if(zip_SMALLER(tree, v, zip_heap[j]))
1744 	    break;
1745 
1746 	// Exchange v with the smallest son
1747 	zip_heap[k] = zip_heap[j];
1748 	k = j;
1749 
1750 	// And continue down the tree, setting j to the left son of k
1751 	j <<= 1;
1752     }
1753     zip_heap[k] = v;
1754 }
1755 
1756 /* ==========================================================================
1757  * Compute the optimal bit lengths for a tree and update the total bit length
1758  * for the current block.
1759  * IN assertion: the fields freq and dad are set, heap[heap_max] and
1760  *    above are the tree nodes sorted by increasing frequency.
1761  * OUT assertions: the field len is set to the optimal bit length, the
1762  *     array bl_count contains the frequencies for each bit length.
1763  *     The length opt_len is updated; static_len is also updated if stree is
1764  *     not null.
1765  */
1766 var zip_gen_bitlen = function(desc) { // the tree descriptor
1767     var tree		= desc.dyn_tree;
1768     var extra		= desc.extra_bits;
1769     var base		= desc.extra_base;
1770     var max_code	= desc.max_code;
1771     var max_length	= desc.max_length;
1772     var stree		= desc.static_tree;
1773     var h;		// heap index
1774     var n, m;		// iterate over the tree elements
1775     var bits;		// bit length
1776     var xbits;		// extra bits
1777     var f;		// frequency
1778     var overflow = 0;	// number of elements with bit length too large
1779 
1780     for(bits = 0; bits <= zip_MAX_BITS; bits++)
1781 	zip_bl_count[bits] = 0;
1782 
1783     /* In a first pass, compute the optimal bit lengths (which may
1784      * overflow in the case of the bit length tree).
1785      */
1786     tree[zip_heap[zip_heap_max]].dl = 0; // root of the heap
1787 
1788     for(h = zip_heap_max + 1; h < zip_HEAP_SIZE; h++) {
1789 	n = zip_heap[h];
1790 	bits = tree[tree[n].dl].dl + 1;
1791 	if(bits > max_length) {
1792 	    bits = max_length;
1793 	    overflow++;
1794 	}
1795 	tree[n].dl = bits;
1796 	// We overwrite tree[n].dl which is no longer needed
1797 
1798 	if(n > max_code)
1799 	    continue; // not a leaf node
1800 
1801 	zip_bl_count[bits]++;
1802 	xbits = 0;
1803 	if(n >= base)
1804 	    xbits = extra[n - base];
1805 	f = tree[n].fc;
1806 	zip_opt_len += f * (bits + xbits);
1807 	if(stree != null)
1808 	    zip_static_len += f * (stree[n].dl + xbits);
1809     }
1810     if(overflow == 0)
1811 	return;
1812 
1813     // This happens for example on obj2 and pic of the Calgary corpus
1814 
1815     // Find the first bit length which could increase:
1816     do {
1817 	bits = max_length - 1;
1818 	while(zip_bl_count[bits] == 0)
1819 	    bits--;
1820 	zip_bl_count[bits]--;		// move one leaf down the tree
1821 	zip_bl_count[bits + 1] += 2;	// move one overflow item as its brother
1822 	zip_bl_count[max_length]--;
1823 	/* The brother of the overflow item also moves one step up,
1824 	 * but this does not affect bl_count[max_length]
1825 	 */
1826 	overflow -= 2;
1827     } while(overflow > 0);
1828 
1829     /* Now recompute all bit lengths, scanning in increasing frequency.
1830      * h is still equal to HEAP_SIZE. (It is simpler to reconstruct all
1831      * lengths instead of fixing only the wrong ones. This idea is taken
1832      * from 'ar' written by Haruhiko Okumura.)
1833      */
1834     for(bits = max_length; bits != 0; bits--) {
1835 	n = zip_bl_count[bits];
1836 	while(n != 0) {
1837 	    m = zip_heap[--h];
1838 	    if(m > max_code)
1839 		continue;
1840 	    if(tree[m].dl != bits) {
1841 		zip_opt_len += (bits - tree[m].dl) * tree[m].fc;
1842 		tree[m].fc = bits;
1843 	    }
1844 	    n--;
1845 	}
1846     }
1847 }
1848 
1849   /* ==========================================================================
1850    * Generate the codes for a given tree and bit counts (which need not be
1851    * optimal).
1852    * IN assertion: the array bl_count contains the bit length statistics for
1853    * the given tree and the field len is set for all tree elements.
1854    * OUT assertion: the field code is set for all tree elements of non
1855    *     zero code length.
1856    */
1857 var zip_gen_codes = function(tree,	// the tree to decorate
1858 		   max_code) {	// largest code with non zero frequency
1859     var next_code = new Array(zip_MAX_BITS+1); // next code value for each bit length
1860     var code = 0;		// running code value
1861     var bits;			// bit index
1862     var n;			// code index
1863 
1864     /* The distribution counts are first used to generate the code values
1865      * without bit reversal.
1866      */
1867     for(bits = 1; bits <= zip_MAX_BITS; bits++) {
1868 	code = ((code + zip_bl_count[bits-1]) << 1);
1869 	next_code[bits] = code;
1870     }
1871 
1872     /* Check that the bit counts in bl_count are consistent. The last code
1873      * must be all ones.
1874      */
1875 //    Assert (code + encoder->bl_count[MAX_BITS]-1 == (1<<MAX_BITS)-1,
1876 //	    "inconsistent bit counts");
1877 //    Tracev((stderr,"\ngen_codes: max_code %d ", max_code));
1878 
1879     for(n = 0; n <= max_code; n++) {
1880 	var len = tree[n].dl;
1881 	if(len == 0)
1882 	    continue;
1883 	// Now reverse the bits
1884 	tree[n].fc = zip_bi_reverse(next_code[len]++, len);
1885 
1886 //      Tracec(tree != static_ltree, (stderr,"\nn %3d %c l %2d c %4x (%x) ",
1887 //	  n, (isgraph(n) ? n : ' '), len, tree[n].fc, next_code[len]-1));
1888     }
1889 }
1890 
1891 /* ==========================================================================
1892  * Construct one Huffman tree and assigns the code bit strings and lengths.
1893  * Update the total bit length for the current block.
1894  * IN assertion: the field freq is set for all tree elements.
1895  * OUT assertions: the fields len and code are set to the optimal bit length
1896  *     and corresponding code. The length opt_len is updated; static_len is
1897  *     also updated if stree is not null. The field max_code is set.
1898  */
1899 var zip_build_tree = function(desc) { // the tree descriptor
1900     var tree	= desc.dyn_tree;
1901     var stree	= desc.static_tree;
1902     var elems	= desc.elems;
1903     var n, m;		// iterate over heap elements
1904     var max_code = -1;	// largest code with non zero frequency
1905     var node = elems;	// next internal node of the tree
1906 
1907     /* Construct the initial heap, with least frequent element in
1908      * heap[SMALLEST]. The sons of heap[n] are heap[2*n] and heap[2*n+1].
1909      * heap[0] is not used.
1910      */
1911     zip_heap_len = 0;
1912     zip_heap_max = zip_HEAP_SIZE;
1913 
1914     for(n = 0; n < elems; n++) {
1915 	if(tree[n].fc != 0) {
1916 	    zip_heap[++zip_heap_len] = max_code = n;
1917 	    zip_depth[n] = 0;
1918 	} else
1919 	    tree[n].dl = 0;
1920     }
1921 
1922     /* The pkzip format requires that at least one distance code exists,
1923      * and that at least one bit should be sent even if there is only one
1924      * possible code. So to avoid special checks later on we force at least
1925      * two codes of non zero frequency.
1926      */
1927     while(zip_heap_len < 2) {
1928 	var xnew = zip_heap[++zip_heap_len] = (max_code < 2 ? ++max_code : 0);
1929 	tree[xnew].fc = 1;
1930 	zip_depth[xnew] = 0;
1931 	zip_opt_len--;
1932 	if(stree != null)
1933 	    zip_static_len -= stree[xnew].dl;
1934 	// new is 0 or 1 so it does not have extra bits
1935     }
1936     desc.max_code = max_code;
1937 
1938     /* The elements heap[heap_len/2+1 .. heap_len] are leaves of the tree,
1939      * establish sub-heaps of increasing lengths:
1940      */
1941     for(n = zip_heap_len >> 1; n >= 1; n--)
1942 	zip_pqdownheap(tree, n);
1943 
1944     /* Construct the Huffman tree by repeatedly combining the least two
1945      * frequent nodes.
1946      */
1947     do {
1948 	n = zip_heap[zip_SMALLEST];
1949 	zip_heap[zip_SMALLEST] = zip_heap[zip_heap_len--];
1950 	zip_pqdownheap(tree, zip_SMALLEST);
1951 
1952 	m = zip_heap[zip_SMALLEST];  // m = node of next least frequency
1953 
1954 	// keep the nodes sorted by frequency
1955 	zip_heap[--zip_heap_max] = n;
1956 	zip_heap[--zip_heap_max] = m;
1957 
1958 	// Create a new node father of n and m
1959 	tree[node].fc = tree[n].fc + tree[m].fc;
1960 //	depth[node] = (char)(MAX(depth[n], depth[m]) + 1);
1961 	if(zip_depth[n] > zip_depth[m] + 1)
1962 	    zip_depth[node] = zip_depth[n];
1963 	else
1964 	    zip_depth[node] = zip_depth[m] + 1;
1965 	tree[n].dl = tree[m].dl = node;
1966 
1967 	// and insert the new node in the heap
1968 	zip_heap[zip_SMALLEST] = node++;
1969 	zip_pqdownheap(tree, zip_SMALLEST);
1970 
1971     } while(zip_heap_len >= 2);
1972 
1973     zip_heap[--zip_heap_max] = zip_heap[zip_SMALLEST];
1974 
1975     /* At this point, the fields freq and dad are set. We can now
1976      * generate the bit lengths.
1977      */
1978     zip_gen_bitlen(desc);
1979 
1980     // The field len is now set, we can generate the bit codes
1981     zip_gen_codes(tree, max_code);
1982 }
1983 
1984 /* ==========================================================================
1985  * Scan a literal or distance tree to determine the frequencies of the codes
1986  * in the bit length tree. Updates opt_len to take into account the repeat
1987  * counts. (The contribution of the bit length codes will be added later
1988  * during the construction of bl_tree.)
1989  */
1990 var zip_scan_tree = function(tree,// the tree to be scanned
1991 		       max_code) {  // and its largest code of non zero frequency
1992     var n;			// iterates over all tree elements
1993     var prevlen = -1;		// last emitted length
1994     var curlen;			// length of current code
1995     var nextlen = tree[0].dl;	// length of next code
1996     var count = 0;		// repeat count of the current code
1997     var max_count = 7;		// max repeat count
1998     var min_count = 4;		// min repeat count
1999 
2000     if(nextlen == 0) {
2001 	max_count = 138;
2002 	min_count = 3;
2003     }
2004     tree[max_code + 1].dl = 0xffff; // guard
2005 
2006     for(n = 0; n <= max_code; n++) {
2007 	curlen = nextlen;
2008 	nextlen = tree[n + 1].dl;
2009 	if(++count < max_count && curlen == nextlen)
2010 	    continue;
2011 	else if(count < min_count)
2012 	    zip_bl_tree[curlen].fc += count;
2013 	else if(curlen != 0) {
2014 	    if(curlen != prevlen)
2015 		zip_bl_tree[curlen].fc++;
2016 	    zip_bl_tree[zip_REP_3_6].fc++;
2017 	} else if(count <= 10)
2018 	    zip_bl_tree[zip_REPZ_3_10].fc++;
2019 	else
2020 	    zip_bl_tree[zip_REPZ_11_138].fc++;
2021 	count = 0; prevlen = curlen;
2022 	if(nextlen == 0) {
2023 	    max_count = 138;
2024 	    min_count = 3;
2025 	} else if(curlen == nextlen) {
2026 	    max_count = 6;
2027 	    min_count = 3;
2028 	} else {
2029 	    max_count = 7;
2030 	    min_count = 4;
2031 	}
2032     }
2033 }
2034 
2035   /* ==========================================================================
2036    * Send a literal or distance tree in compressed form, using the codes in
2037    * bl_tree.
2038    */
2039 var zip_send_tree = function(tree, // the tree to be scanned
2040 		   max_code) { // and its largest code of non zero frequency
2041     var n;			// iterates over all tree elements
2042     var prevlen = -1;		// last emitted length
2043     var curlen;			// length of current code
2044     var nextlen = tree[0].dl;	// length of next code
2045     var count = 0;		// repeat count of the current code
2046     var max_count = 7;		// max repeat count
2047     var min_count = 4;		// min repeat count
2048 
2049     /* tree[max_code+1].dl = -1; */  /* guard already set */
2050     if(nextlen == 0) {
2051       max_count = 138;
2052       min_count = 3;
2053     }
2054 
2055     for(n = 0; n <= max_code; n++) {
2056 	curlen = nextlen;
2057 	nextlen = tree[n+1].dl;
2058 	if(++count < max_count && curlen == nextlen) {
2059 	    continue;
2060 	} else if(count < min_count) {
2061 	    do { zip_SEND_CODE(curlen, zip_bl_tree); } while(--count != 0);
2062 	} else if(curlen != 0) {
2063 	    if(curlen != prevlen) {
2064 		zip_SEND_CODE(curlen, zip_bl_tree);
2065 		count--;
2066 	    }
2067 	    // Assert(count >= 3 && count <= 6, " 3_6?");
2068 	    zip_SEND_CODE(zip_REP_3_6, zip_bl_tree);
2069 	    zip_send_bits(count - 3, 2);
2070 	} else if(count <= 10) {
2071 	    zip_SEND_CODE(zip_REPZ_3_10, zip_bl_tree);
2072 	    zip_send_bits(count-3, 3);
2073 	} else {
2074 	    zip_SEND_CODE(zip_REPZ_11_138, zip_bl_tree);
2075 	    zip_send_bits(count-11, 7);
2076 	}
2077 	count = 0;
2078 	prevlen = curlen;
2079 	if(nextlen == 0) {
2080 	    max_count = 138;
2081 	    min_count = 3;
2082 	} else if(curlen == nextlen) {
2083 	    max_count = 6;
2084 	    min_count = 3;
2085 	} else {
2086 	    max_count = 7;
2087 	    min_count = 4;
2088 	}
2089     }
2090 }
2091 
2092 /* ==========================================================================
2093  * Construct the Huffman tree for the bit lengths and return the index in
2094  * bl_order of the last bit length code to send.
2095  */
2096 var zip_build_bl_tree = function() {
2097     var max_blindex;  // index of last bit length code of non zero freq
2098 
2099     // Determine the bit length frequencies for literal and distance trees
2100     zip_scan_tree(zip_dyn_ltree, zip_l_desc.max_code);
2101     zip_scan_tree(zip_dyn_dtree, zip_d_desc.max_code);
2102 
2103     // Build the bit length tree:
2104     zip_build_tree(zip_bl_desc);
2105     /* opt_len now includes the length of the tree representations, except
2106      * the lengths of the bit lengths codes and the 5+5+4 bits for the counts.
2107      */
2108 
2109     /* Determine the number of bit length codes to send. The pkzip format
2110      * requires that at least 4 bit length codes be sent. (appnote.txt says
2111      * 3 but the actual value used is 4.)
2112      */
2113     for(max_blindex = zip_BL_CODES-1; max_blindex >= 3; max_blindex--) {
2114 	if(zip_bl_tree[zip_bl_order[max_blindex]].dl != 0) break;
2115     }
2116     /* Update opt_len to include the bit length tree and counts */
2117     zip_opt_len += 3*(max_blindex+1) + 5+5+4;
2118 //    Tracev((stderr, "\ndyn trees: dyn %ld, stat %ld",
2119 //	    encoder->opt_len, encoder->static_len));
2120 
2121     return max_blindex;
2122 }

2124 /* ==========================================================================
2125  * Send the header for a block using dynamic Huffman trees: the counts, the
2126  * lengths of the bit length codes, the literal tree and the distance tree.
2127  * IN assertion: lcodes >= 257, dcodes >= 1, blcodes >= 4.
2128  */
2129 var zip_send_all_trees = function(lcodes, dcodes, blcodes) { // number of codes for each tree
2130     var rank; // index in bl_order
2131 
2132 //    Assert (lcodes >= 257 && dcodes >= 1 && blcodes >= 4, "not enough codes");
2133 //    Assert (lcodes <= L_CODES && dcodes <= D_CODES && blcodes <= BL_CODES,
2134 //	    "too many codes");
2135 //    Tracev((stderr, "\nbl counts: "));
2136     zip_send_bits(lcodes-257, 5); // not +255 as stated in appnote.txt
2137     zip_send_bits(dcodes-1,   5);
2138     zip_send_bits(blcodes-4,  4); // not -3 as stated in appnote.txt
2139     for(rank = 0; rank < blcodes; rank++) {
2140 //      Tracev((stderr, "\nbl code %2d ", bl_order[rank]));
2141 	zip_send_bits(zip_bl_tree[zip_bl_order[rank]].dl, 3);
2142     }
2143 
2144     // send the literal tree
2145     zip_send_tree(zip_dyn_ltree,lcodes-1);
2146 
2147     // send the distance tree
2148     zip_send_tree(zip_dyn_dtree,dcodes-1);
2149 }

2151 /* ==========================================================================
2152  * Determine the best encoding for the current block: dynamic trees, static
2153  * trees or store, and output the encoded block to the zip file.
2154  */
2155 var zip_flush_block = function(eof) { // true if this is the last block for a file
2156     var opt_lenb, static_lenb; // opt_len and static_len in bytes
2157     var max_blindex;	// index of last bit length code of non zero freq
2158     var stored_len;	// length of input block
2159 
2160     stored_len = zip_strstart - zip_block_start;
2161     zip_flag_buf[zip_last_flags] = zip_flags; // Save the flags for the last 8 items
2162 
2163     // Construct the literal and distance trees
2164     zip_build_tree(zip_l_desc);
2165 //    Tracev((stderr, "\nlit data: dyn %ld, stat %ld",
2166 //	    encoder->opt_len, encoder->static_len));
2167 
2168     zip_build_tree(zip_d_desc);
2169 //    Tracev((stderr, "\ndist data: dyn %ld, stat %ld",
2170 //	    encoder->opt_len, encoder->static_len));
2171     /* At this point, opt_len and static_len are the total bit lengths of
2172      * the compressed block data, excluding the tree representations.
2173      */
2174 
2175     /* Build the bit length tree for the above two trees, and get the index
2176      * in bl_order of the last bit length code to send.
2177      */
2178     max_blindex = zip_build_bl_tree();
2179 
2180     // Determine the best encoding. Compute first the block length in bytes
2181     opt_lenb	= (zip_opt_len   +3+7)>>3;
2182     static_lenb = (zip_static_len+3+7)>>3;
2183 
2184 //    Trace((stderr, "\nopt %lu(%lu) stat %lu(%lu) stored %lu lit %u dist %u ",
2185 //	   opt_lenb, encoder->opt_len,
2186 //	   static_lenb, encoder->static_len, stored_len,
2187 //	   encoder->last_lit, encoder->last_dist));
2188 
2189     if(static_lenb <= opt_lenb)
2190 	opt_lenb = static_lenb;
2191     if(stored_len + 4 <= opt_lenb // 4: two words for the lengths
2192        && zip_block_start >= 0) {
2193 	var i;
2194 
2195 	/* The test buf != NULL is only necessary if LIT_BUFSIZE > WSIZE.
2196 	 * Otherwise we can't have processed more than WSIZE input bytes since
2197 	 * the last block flush, because compression would have been
2198 	 * successful. If LIT_BUFSIZE <= WSIZE, it is never too late to
2199 	 * transform a block into a stored block.
2200 	 */
2201 	zip_send_bits((zip_STORED_BLOCK<<1)+eof, 3);  /* send block type */
2202 	zip_bi_windup();		 /* align on byte boundary */
2203 	zip_put_short(stored_len);
2204 	zip_put_short(~stored_len);
2205 
2206       // copy block
2207 /*
2208       p = &window[block_start];
2209       for(i = 0; i < stored_len; i++)
2210 	put_byte(p[i]);
2211 */
2212 	for(i = 0; i < stored_len; i++)
2213 	    zip_put_byte(zip_window[zip_block_start + i]);
2214 
2215     } else if(static_lenb == opt_lenb) {
2216 	zip_send_bits((zip_STATIC_TREES<<1)+eof, 3);
2217 	zip_compress_block(zip_static_ltree, zip_static_dtree);
2218     } else {
2219 	zip_send_bits((zip_DYN_TREES<<1)+eof, 3);
2220 	zip_send_all_trees(zip_l_desc.max_code+1,
2221 			   zip_d_desc.max_code+1,
2222 			   max_blindex+1);
2223 	zip_compress_block(zip_dyn_ltree, zip_dyn_dtree);
2224     }
2225 
2226     zip_init_block();
2227 
2228     if(eof != 0)
2229 	zip_bi_windup();
2230 }

2232 /* ==========================================================================
2233  * Save the match info and tally the frequency counts. Return true if
2234  * the current block must be flushed.
2235  */
2236 var zip_ct_tally = function(
2237 	dist, // distance of matched string
2238 	lc) { // match length-MIN_MATCH or unmatched char (if dist==0)
2239     zip_l_buf[zip_last_lit++] = lc;
2240     if(dist == 0) {
2241 	// lc is the unmatched char
2242 	zip_dyn_ltree[lc].fc++;
2243     } else {
2244 	// Here, lc is the match length - MIN_MATCH
2245 	dist--;		    // dist = match distance - 1
2246 //      Assert((ush)dist < (ush)MAX_DIST &&
2247 //	     (ush)lc <= (ush)(MAX_MATCH-MIN_MATCH) &&
2248 //	     (ush)D_CODE(dist) < (ush)D_CODES,  "ct_tally: bad match");
2249 
2250 	zip_dyn_ltree[zip_length_code[lc]+zip_LITERALS+1].fc++;
2251 	zip_dyn_dtree[zip_D_CODE(dist)].fc++;
2252 
2253 	zip_d_buf[zip_last_dist++] = dist;
2254 	zip_flags |= zip_flag_bit;
2255     }
2256     zip_flag_bit <<= 1;
2257 
2258     // Output the flags if they fill a byte
2259     if((zip_last_lit & 7) == 0) {
2260 	zip_flag_buf[zip_last_flags++] = zip_flags;
2261 	zip_flags = 0;
2262 	zip_flag_bit = 1;
2263     }
2264     // Try to guess if it is profitable to stop the current block here
2265     if(zip_compr_level > 2 && (zip_last_lit & 0xfff) == 0) {
2266 	// Compute an upper bound for the compressed length
2267 	var out_length = zip_last_lit * 8;
2268 	var in_length = zip_strstart - zip_block_start;
2269 	var dcode;
2270 
2271 	for(dcode = 0; dcode < zip_D_CODES; dcode++) {
2272 	    out_length += zip_dyn_dtree[dcode].fc * (5 + zip_extra_dbits[dcode]);
2273 	}
2274 	out_length >>= 3;
2275 //      Trace((stderr,"\nlast_lit %u, last_dist %u, in %ld, out ~%ld(%ld%%) ",
2276 //	     encoder->last_lit, encoder->last_dist, in_length, out_length,
2277 //	     100L - out_length*100L/in_length));
2278 	if(zip_last_dist < parseInt(zip_last_lit/2) &&
2279 	   out_length < parseInt(in_length/2))
2280 	    return true;
2281     }
2282     return (zip_last_lit == zip_LIT_BUFSIZE-1 ||
2283 	    zip_last_dist == zip_DIST_BUFSIZE);
2284     /* We avoid equality with LIT_BUFSIZE because of wraparound at 64K
2285      * on 16 bit machines and because stored blocks are restricted to
2286      * 64K-1 bytes.
2287      */
2288 }

2291    * Send the block data compressed using the given Huffman trees
2292    */
2293 var zip_compress_block = function(
2294 	ltree,	// literal tree
2295 	dtree) {	// distance tree
2296     var dist;		// distance of matched string
2297     var lc;		// match length or unmatched char (if dist == 0)
2298     var lx = 0;		// running index in l_buf
2299     var dx = 0;		// running index in d_buf
2300     var fx = 0;		// running index in flag_buf
2301     var flag = 0;	// current flags
2302     var code;		// the code to send
2303     var extra;		// number of extra bits to send
2304 
2305     if(zip_last_lit != 0) do {
2306 	if((lx & 7) == 0)
2307 	    flag = zip_flag_buf[fx++];
2308 	lc = zip_l_buf[lx++] & 0xff;
2309 	if((flag & 1) == 0) {
2310 	    zip_SEND_CODE(lc, ltree); /* send a literal byte */
2311 //	Tracecv(isgraph(lc), (stderr," '%c' ", lc));
2312 	} else {
2313 	    // Here, lc is the match length - MIN_MATCH
2314 	    code = zip_length_code[lc];
2315 	    zip_SEND_CODE(code+zip_LITERALS+1, ltree); // send the length code
2316 	    extra = zip_extra_lbits[code];
2317 	    if(extra != 0) {
2318 		lc -= zip_base_length[code];
2319 		zip_send_bits(lc, extra); // send the extra length bits
2320 	    }
2321 	    dist = zip_d_buf[dx++];
2322 	    // Here, dist is the match distance - 1
2323 	    code = zip_D_CODE(dist);
2324 //	Assert (code < D_CODES, "bad d_code");
2325 
2326 	    zip_SEND_CODE(code, dtree);	  // send the distance code
2327 	    extra = zip_extra_dbits[code];
2328 	    if(extra != 0) {
2329 		dist -= zip_base_dist[code];
2330 		zip_send_bits(dist, extra);   // send the extra distance bits
2331 	    }
2332 	} // literal or match pair ?
2333 	flag >>= 1;
2334     } while(lx < zip_last_lit);
2335 
2336     zip_SEND_CODE(zip_END_BLOCK, ltree);
2337 }

2339 /* ==========================================================================
2340  * Send a value on a given number of bits.
2341  * IN assertion: length <= 16 and value fits in length bits.
2342  */
2343 var zip_Buf_size = 16; // bit size of bi_buf
2344 var zip_send_bits = function(
2345 	value,	// value to send
2346 	length) {	// number of bits
2347     /* If not enough room in bi_buf, use (valid) bits from bi_buf and
2348      * (16 - bi_valid) bits from value, leaving (width - (16-bi_valid))
2349      * unused bits in value.
2350      */
2351     if(zip_bi_valid > zip_Buf_size - length) {
2352 	zip_bi_buf |= (value << zip_bi_valid);
2353 	zip_put_short(zip_bi_buf);
2354 	zip_bi_buf = (value >> (zip_Buf_size - zip_bi_valid));
2355 	zip_bi_valid += length - zip_Buf_size;
2356     } else {
2357 	zip_bi_buf |= value << zip_bi_valid;
2358 	zip_bi_valid += length;
2359     }
2360 }

2362 /* ==========================================================================
2363  * Reverse the first len bits of a code, using straightforward code (a faster
2364  * method would use a table)
2365  * IN assertion: 1 <= len <= 15
2366  */
2367 var zip_bi_reverse = function(
2368 	code,	// the value to invert
2369 	len) {	// its bit length
2370     var res = 0;
2371     do {
2372 	res |= code & 1;
2373 	code >>= 1;
2374 	res <<= 1;
2375     } while(--len > 0);
2376     return res >> 1;
2377 }

2379 /* ==========================================================================
2380  * Write out any remaining bits in an incomplete byte.
2381  */

2383     if(zip_bi_valid > 8) {
2384 	zip_put_short(zip_bi_buf);
2385     } else if(zip_bi_valid > 0) {
2386 	zip_put_byte(zip_bi_buf);
2387     }
2388     zip_bi_buf = 0;
2389     zip_bi_valid = 0;
2390 }

3067 		/**
3068 		* Analyzes image colors and creates color map.
3069 		*/
3070 		
3071 		var analyzePixels = function analyzePixels()/*void*/
3072 		{
3073 		    
3074 			var len/*int*/ = pixels.length;
3075 		    var nPix/*int*/ = len / 3;
3076 		    indexedPixels = [];
3077 		    var nq/*NeuQuant*/ = new NeuQuant(pixels, len, sample);
3078 		    // initialize quantizer
3079 		    colorTab = nq.process(); // create reduced palette
3080 		    // map image pixels to new palette
3081 		    var k/*int*/ = 0;
3082 		    for (var j/*int*/ = 0; j < nPix; j++) {
3083 		      var index/*int*/ = nq.map(pixels[k++] & 0xff, pixels[k++] & 0xff, pixels[k++] & 0xff);
3084 		      usedEntry[index] = true;
3085 		      indexedPixels[j] = index;
3086 		    }
3087 		    pixels = null;
3088 		    colorDepth = 8;
3089 		    palSize = 7;
3090 		    // get closest match to transparent color if specified
3091 		    if (transparent != null) {
3092 		      transIndex = findClosest(transparent);
3093 		    }
3094 		}

3096 		/**
3097 		* Returns index of palette color closest to c
3098 		*
3099 		*/
3100 		
3101 		var findClosest = function findClosest(c/*Number*/)/*int*/
3102 		{
3103 			
3104 			if (colorTab == null) return -1;
3105 		    var r/*int*/ = (c & 0xFF0000) >> 16;
3106 		    var g/*int*/ = (c & 0x00FF00) >> 8;
3107 		    var b/*int*/ = (c & 0x0000FF);
3108 		    var minpos/*int*/ = 0;
3109 		    var dmin/*int*/ = 256 * 256 * 256;
3110 		    var len/*int*/ = colorTab.length;
3111 			
3112 		    for (var i/*int*/ = 0; i < len;) {
3113 		      var dr/*int*/ = r - (colorTab[i++] & 0xff);
3114 		      var dg/*int*/ = g - (colorTab[i++] & 0xff);
3115 		      var db/*int*/ = b - (colorTab[i] & 0xff);
3116 		      var d/*int*/ = dr * dr + dg * dg + db * db;
3117 		      var index/*int*/ = i / 3;
3118 		      if (usedEntry[index] && (d < dmin)) {
3119 		        dmin = d;
3120 		        minpos = index;
3121 		      }
3122 		      i++;
3123 		    }
3124 		    return minpos;
3125 			
3126 		}

3340 	{
3341 	    var exports = {};
3342 		/*private_static*/ var netsize/*int*/ = 256; /* number of colours used */
3343 		
3344 		/* four primes near 500 - assume no image has a length so large */
3345 		/* that it is divisible by all four primes */
3346 		
3347 		/*private_static*/ var prime1/*int*/ = 499;
3348 		/*private_static*/ var prime2/*int*/ = 491;
3349 		/*private_static*/ var prime3/*int*/ = 487;
3350 		/*private_static*/ var prime4/*int*/ = 503;

3353 		/* minimum size for input image */

3355 		* Program Skeleton ---------------- [select samplefac in range 1..30] [read
3356 		* image from input file] pic = (unsigned char*) malloc(3*width*height);
3357 		* initnet(pic,3*width*height,samplefac); learn(); unbiasnet(); [write output
3358 		* image header, using writecolourmap(f)] inxbuild(); write output image using
3359 		* inxsearch(b,g,r)
3360 		*/

3368 		/*private_static*/ var ncycles/*int*/ = 100; /* no. of learning cycles */
3369 		
3370 		/* defs for freq and bias */
3371 		/*private_static*/ var intbiasshift/*int*/ = 16; /* bias for fractions */
3372 		/*private_static*/ var intbias/*int*/ = (1 << intbiasshift);
3373 		/*private_static*/ var gammashift/*int*/ = 10; /* gamma = 1024 */
3374 		/*private_static*/ var gamma/*int*/ = (1 << gammashift);
3375 		/*private_static*/ var betashift/*int*/ = 10;
3376 		/*private_static*/ var beta/*int*/ = (intbias >> betashift); /* beta = 1/1024 */
3377 		/*private_static*/ var betagamma/*int*/ = (intbias << (gammashift - betashift));
3378 		
3379 		/* defs for decreasing radius factor */

3381 	                                                         * for 256 cols, radius
3382 	                                                         * starts
3383 	                                                         */
3384

3386 		/*private_static*/ var radiusbias/*int*/ = (1 << radiusbiasshift);

3388 	                                                                   * and
3389 	                                                                   * decreases
3390 	                                                                   * by a
3391 	                                                                   */
3392

3394

3403 		/*private_static*/ var alpharadbshift/*int*/ = (alphabiasshift + radbiasshift);

3405 		/*private_static*/ var alpharadbias/*int*/ = (1 << alpharadbshift);

3407 		/*
3408 		* Types and Global Variables --------------------------

3410

3413 		/*private*/ var samplefac/*int*/; /* sampling factor 1..30 */

3426 		var NeuQuant = exports.NeuQuant = function NeuQuant(thepic/*ByteArray*/, len/*int*/, sample/*int*/)
3427 		{
3428 			
3429 			var i/*int*/;
3430 			var p/*Array*/;
3431 			
3432 			thepicture = thepic;
3433 			lengthcount = len;
3434 			samplefac = sample;
3435 			
3436 			network = new Array(netsize);
3437 			
3438 			for (i = 0; i < netsize; i++)
3439 			{
3440

3503 				}

3508

3539 				
3540 			  }
3541

3546 			
3547 	   }

3607 			   }
3608

3629 			   
3630 			   i++;
3631 			   
3632 			   if (delta == 0) delta = 1;
3633 			   
3634 			   if (i % delta == 0)
3635 			   
3636 			   {
3637 				   
3638 				   alpha -= alpha / alphadec;
3639 				   radius -= radius / radiusdec;
3640 				   rad = radius >> radiusbiasshift;
3641 				   
3642 				   if (rad <= 1) rad = 0;
3643 				   
3644 				   for (j = 0; j < rad; j++) radpower[j] = alpha * (((rad * rad - j * j) * radbias) / (rad * rad));
3645 				   
3646 			   }
3647 			   
3648 		   }
3649

3788 	  
3789 	  {
3790

3792 	    var j/*int*/;
3793

3795 		{

3797 	      network[i][1] >>= netbiasshift;
3798 	      network[i][2] >>= netbiasshift;
3799 	      network[i][3] = i; /* record colour no */
3800 	    }

3805 	  * Move adjacent neurons by precomputed alpha*(1-((i-j)^2/[r]^2)) in

3808 	  */

3810 	  var alterneigh = function alterneigh(rad/*int*/, i/*int*/, b/*int*/, g/*int*/, r/*int*/)/*void*/
3811 	  
3812 	  {
3813 		  
3814 		  var j/*int*/;
3815 		  var k/*int*/;
3816 		  var lo/*int*/;
3817 		  var hi/*int*/;
3818 		  var a/*int*/;

3820 		  
3821 		  var p/*Array*/;
3822 		  
3823 		  lo = i - rad;
3824 		  if (lo < -1) lo = -1;
3825 		  
3826 		  hi = i + rad;
3827 		  
3828 		  if (hi > netsize) hi = netsize;
3829 		  
3830 		  j = i + 1;
3831 		  k = i - 1;
3832 		  m = 1;
3833 		  
3834 		  while ((j < hi) || (k > lo))
3835 		  
3836 		  {
3837 			  
3838 			  a = radpower[m++];
3839 			  
3840 			  if (j < hi)
3841 			  
3842 			  {
3843 				  
3844 				  p = network[j++];
3845 				  
3846 				  try {
3847 					  
3848 					  p[0] -= (a * (p[0] - b)) / alpharadbias;
3849 					  p[1] -= (a * (p[1] - g)) / alpharadbias;
3850 					  p[2] -= (a * (p[2] - r)) / alpharadbias;
3851 					  
3852 					  } catch (e/*Error*/) {} // prevents 1.3 miscompilation
3853 					  
3854 				}
3855 				
3856 				if (k > lo)
3857 				
3858 				{
3859 					
3860 					p = network[k--];
3861 					
3862 					try
3863 					{
3864 						
3865 						p[0] -= (a * (p[0] - b)) / alpharadbias;
3866 						p[1] -= (a * (p[1] - g)) / alpharadbias;
3867 						p[2] -= (a * (p[2] - r)) / alpharadbias;
3868 						
3869 					} catch (e/*Error*/) {}
3870 					
3871 				}
3872 				
3873 		  }

3879 	  * ----------------------------------------------------

3882 	  var altersingle = function altersingle(alpha/*int*/, i/*int*/, b/*int*/, g/*int*/, r/*int*/)/*void*/ 
3883 	  {

3885 		  /* alter hit neuron */
3886 		  var n/*Array*/ = network[i];
3887 		  n[0] -= (alpha * (n[0] - b)) / initalpha;
3888 		  n[1] -= (alpha * (n[1] - g)) / initalpha;
3889 		  n[2] -= (alpha * (n[2] - r)) / initalpha;
3890

3894 	  * Search for biased BGR values ----------------------------
3895 	  */
3896 	  
3897 	  var contest = function contest(b/*int*/, g/*int*/, r/*int*/)/*int*/
3898 	  {
3899 		  
3900 		  /* finds closest neuron (min dist) and updates freq */
3901 		  /* finds best neuron (min dist-bias) and returns position */
3902 		  /* for frequently chosen neurons, freq[i] is high and bias[i] is negative */
3903 		  /* bias[i] = gamma*((1/netsize)-freq[i]) */
3904 		  
3905 		  var i/*int*/;
3906 		  var dist/*int*/;
3907 		  var a/*int*/;
3908 		  var biasdist/*int*/;
3909 		  var betafreq/*int*/;
3910 		  var bestpos/*int*/;
3911 		  var bestbiaspos/*int*/;
3912 		  var bestd/*int*/;
3913 		  var bestbiasd/*int*/;
3914 		  var n/*Array*/;
3915 		  
3916 		  bestd = ~(1 << 31);
3917 		  bestbiasd = bestd;
3918 		  bestpos = -1;
3919 		  bestbiaspos = bestpos;
3920 		  
3921 		  for (i = 0; i < netsize; i++)
3922 		  
3923 		  {
3924 			  
3925 			  n = network[i];
3926 			  dist = n[0] - b;
3927 			  
3928 			  if (dist < 0) dist = -dist;
3929 			  
3930 			  a = n[1] - g;
3931 			  
3932 			  if (a < 0) a = -a;
3933 			  
3934 			  dist += a;
3935 			  
3936 			  a = n[2] - r;
3937 			  
3938 			  if (a < 0) a = -a;
3939 			  
3940 			  dist += a;
3941 			  
3942 			  if (dist < bestd)
3943 			  
3944 			  {
3945 				  
3946 				  bestd = dist;
3947 				  bestpos = i;
3948 				  
3949 			  }
3950 			  
3951 			  biasdist = dist - ((bias[i]) >> (intbiasshift - netbiasshift));
3952 			  
3953 			  if (biasdist < bestbiasd)
3954 			  
3955 			  {
3956 				  
3957 				  bestbiasd = biasdist;
3958 				  bestbiaspos = i;
3959 				  
3960 			  }
3961 			  
3962 			  betafreq = (freq[i] >> betashift);
3963 			  freq[i] -= betafreq;
3964 			  bias[i] += (betafreq << gammashift);
3965 			  
3966 		  }
3967 		  
3968 		  freq[bestpos] += beta;
3969 		  bias[bestpos] -= betagamma;
3970 		  return (bestbiaspos);
3971 		  
3972 	  }
